00.Summary:
The first portion of this pipeline reads in the Dx.txt file generated by the Python script. The Python script creates a simple 3D microstructure of grains with some number of elements per grain, as shown in Fig. 2 of the reference below:

# G. M. Castelluccio and D. L. McDowell, "Microstructure and mesh sensitivities of mesoscale surrogate driving force measures for transgranular fatigue cracks in polycrystals," Materials Science and Engineering: A, 639, 626 (2015)


NOTE: Users must assign appropriate file locations in the subsequent filters!

03.Summary: The "Create Attribute Matrix" filter below must be changed by the user! The "Tuple Dimensions" should be equal to the number of grains generated by the Python script + 1. For example, for a Dx.txt file with 4 x 10 x 7 grains, this results in 280 grains and so the value in the "Create Attribute Matrix" should be set to 281.

05.Filter_Human_Label: Create Feature Array from Element Array

06.Summary:
Users can simply read in a ".dream3d" file that contains crystallographic information using the PRISMS-Fatigue files at the link below:

https://github.com/prisms-center/Fatigue/tree/main/src


Simply point to one of the .dream3d files to asisgn texture to the microstructure.


The rest of this pipeline assigns orientations and computes other information necessary to perform crystal plasticity finite element method (CPFEM) simulations using PRISMS-Plasticity and PRISMS-Fatigue.
